  "prompt": "In pregnancy, why is tetracycline contraindicated?",
  "response": "Tetracycline is contraindicated during pregnancy because it can cross the placenta and affect fetal development. Specifically, tetracycline is known to interfere with the normal development of bones and teeth in the developing fetus. The use of tetracycline during pregnancy can lead to:\n\n1. **Discoloration of teeth**: Tetracycline can cause permanent yellow or brown staining of the teeth if administered during the second and third trimesters when teeth are forming.\n\n2. **Bone Growth Impairment**: Tetracycline can also affect bone development, potentially leading to abnormalities and reduced growth in the fetal skeleton.\n\nGiven these significant risks, tetracycline is generally avoided in pregnant individuals, and safer alternatives are recommended if antibiotic treatment is necessary.",
